AGI - "Every feminist, every discrimination, every mistreatment to a woman is an attack on the whole society". The president of the republic, Sergio Mattarella, said this in a message on the occasion of the feast of March 8, hoping for the continuation of repressive actions but also educational to prevent gender violence. "At a delicate moment in the life of the international community, I wish to address, on the occasion of March 8, a greeting and a thought of gratitude to all Italians and to all women who work in Italy and contribute to national well-being", we read in the message diffused while continuing to Hiroshima the journey of the Head of State in Japan.
"We have gained full awareness in recent decades that gender equality policies, a right enshrined in our Constitution, have not been resolved only in an advantage for women, but have brought benefits, wealth, positive fruits for the whole community," Mattarella said, "the promotion of rights is in fact equal terms with the civil and economic development of societies." For this reason, he adds, "it is necessary to engage again, with decision and far-sightedness, in order to fill those differences - cultural, wage, education, career development - which remain in some national areas".
<div </div
According to the head of the state, "particular attention is still answered in the face of the plague - shameful and unacceptable - of violence against women: Every feminist, every discrimination, every mistreatment, is an attack on the whole society. We must continue with the work of repression and prevention. But, at the same time, we must continue with an educational action, starting from younger generations, which promotes a culture of effective equality by eradicating stereotypes, prejudices and consolidated habits. There is need, in this great battle of civilization, of the contribution of all, women and men, who must convey - in all contexts - a culture of respect and deceit and reproduction for discriminatory and violent words and actions >.
"Equivalent commitment must be pursued for inclusive family policies that promote free determination: a woman should never be confronted with the dilemma of choosing between family and profession. "Women are particularly effective vehicles for integration and peace. I want to address a thought of solidarity to women who, in every part of the world, are persecuted, imprisoned, subjected to inaudible violence.' To mothers forced to cry their children fallen into war. To women who struggle to see themselves recognized the most basic rights, from health, freedom, education. We do their pain, we hear their voice. The world will be better with strong protagonism of the wisdom and balance of women," concluded the head of the state.&nbsp;&nbsp;
